00:01:14.109 --> 00:01:18.709
The theme for this month is, in whom do you trust?

00:01:18.709 --> 00:01:20.109
Do you trust me?

00:01:20.109 --> 00:01:21.510
I hope so.

00:01:21.510 --> 00:01:23.510
All of us want to be trusted.

00:01:23.510 --> 00:01:27.909
A trust is a basic element of everyday life.

00:01:27.909 --> 00:01:30.909
To trust others is a normal reaction.

00:01:30.909 --> 00:01:34.510
Many of us have traveled on the train or bus.

00:01:34.510 --> 00:01:39.909
Did we worry whether the conductor or driver would bring a safely to our destination?

00:01:39.909 --> 00:01:42.109
Normally, we do not worry.

00:01:42.109 --> 00:01:47.310
We trust an airplane captain to take us safely to our destination.

00:01:47.310 --> 00:01:49.709
We trust that when we enter an elevator

00:01:49.709 --> 00:01:52.510
that it will not crash at the bottom of the shaft

00:01:52.510 --> 00:01:56.510
but safely take us to the desired floor.

00:01:56.510 --> 00:02:01.109
When we marry, we trust that our partner will remain faithful.

00:02:01.109 --> 00:02:04.909
In many situations in life, we need trust.

00:02:04.909 --> 00:02:06.709
What is trust?

00:02:06.709 --> 00:02:15.110
Trust is the firm belief in the reliability, truth or ability of someone or something.

00:02:15.110 --> 00:02:21.110
Webster's dictionary says that it is confidence, a reliance or a resting of the mind

00:02:21.110 --> 00:02:29.909
on the integrity, veracity, justice, friendship, or other sound principle of another person.

00:02:29.909 --> 00:02:37.110
Trust is related to confidence, belief, faith and assurance.

00:02:37.110 --> 00:02:45.310
Experiments conducted by Professor Dr. Mikhail Kosfeld, a professor at a university in Frankfurt, Germany,

00:02:45.310 --> 00:02:53.310
led him to the conclusion that trust is a biologically-based part of human nature.

00:02:53.310 --> 00:02:58.310
Kosfeld discovered that when there's interaction between two people,

00:02:58.310 --> 00:03:03.710
the human brain releases a hormone that stimulates trust.

00:03:03.710 --> 00:03:11.310
It is, in fact, one of the distinguishing features of the human species, Kosfeld states.

00:03:11.310 --> 00:03:16.110
In everyday life, how discouraged some are if they are not trusted.

00:03:16.110 --> 00:03:18.909
The phrase, don't you trust me?

00:03:18.909 --> 00:03:24.710
Is frequently heard with an undertone of sadness or complaint?

00:03:24.710 --> 00:03:29.509
Sometimes children or teenagers ask their parents, don't you trust me?

00:03:29.509 --> 00:03:35.909
When the parents place some restrictions on them, perhaps in connection with leisure time activities?

00:03:35.909 --> 00:03:44.310
Parents do that because they love you young ones and want to prevent any spiritual or physical harm before you.

00:03:44.310 --> 00:03:53.909
If you cooperate, you will see that parents will gradually trust you ever more and grant you more liberty to you.

00:03:53.909 --> 00:03:58.110
You can prove to them that you are trustworthy.

00:03:58.110 --> 00:04:01.110
In the world, many people are not trustworthy.

00:04:01.110 --> 00:04:08.110
